[[[break]]]added at line 10: *lime {code *McDowell's Argument*

McDowell is responding to the apparent conflict between the desire to have one's mental conceptions that are directed towards the world in some way responsive to that world and the desire to be free to construct these (and other) mental conceptions.  In order to elucidate this problem he uses the arguments of Davidson and S??? for the incompatibility of these concepts.

_The argument for incompatibility_

At this stage in my reading the reasons for the position is unclear but I think I have a fairly good grasp of the position itself.  S??? argues for a logical dichotomy between the logical space of reasons (in which normative attitudes of various kinds are constructed) and the logical space of nature (in which empirical descriptions in general and natural-science descriptions in particular are formed).  Because of this dichotomy one cannot construct the normative attitudes towards empirical experience necessary for one to direct one's mind at the world in a satisfactory way without committing the naturalistic fallacy (by trying to construct a normative account in the purely descriptive logical space of nature).

_McDowell's response_

I'm very unclear on the details of McDowell's response at present.  However, he purports to offer a solution in which the dichotomy presented above is maintained but one is still able to construct a normative account of the way one relates to nature.  This seems to hinge on what he terms "second nature", which in some way allows one to extract normative concepts from empirical experience.
----
